# Responsive Design Rules

## Mobile-First Approach

The entire app must be perfectly responsive for tablet and mobile phone usage.

### Responsive Breakpoints
- **Mobile**: Default (no prefix)
- **Tablet**: `sm:` (640px+)
- **Desktop**: `lg:` (1024px+)

### Layout Patterns
```typescript
// ✅ Good responsive classes
<div className="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6 sm:gap-8">
<div className="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-center space-y-2 sm:space-y-0 sm:space-x-3">
<p className="text-sm sm:text-base text-gray-600">

// ✅ Responsive padding/margins
<div className="p-4 sm:p-6 lg:p-8">
<div className="space-y-4 sm:space-y-6 lg:space-y-8">
```

### Navigation Responsiveness  
- Sidebar collapses on mobile
- Navigation adapts to screen size
- Touch-friendly button sizes (minimum 44px)

### Typography Scale
```typescript
// Responsive text sizing
<h1 className="text-xl sm:text-2xl lg:text-3xl">
<p className="text-sm sm:text-base">
```

### Component Responsiveness
- All components must work on mobile
- Test on tablet and phone viewports
- Use responsive grid systems
- Ensure touch targets are adequate

### Development Rules
1. **Mobile-first**: Start with mobile layout, enhance for larger screens
2. **Test all breakpoints**: Verify functionality across device sizes
3. **ConditionalLayout handles main responsive structure**: Don't override in components

